We're excited to welcome Danny Waits to the board!
At this morning's called board meeting, FCBOE members unanimously approved the appointment of Danny Waits to serve as the FCBOE representative for District 5 through the end of 2020 due to Melinda Jeffers resigning and moving out of the district.
Danny Waits ran for the seat unopposed and will begin his official term starting January 1, 2021. Read more here: https://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/rome/news/local/jeffers-not-seeking-reelection-on-county-school-board-waits-announces-candidacy-for-seat/article_388af97a-3f9d-11ea-acad-2f582861fd31.html

A student/employee at Coosa Middle School has tested positive for COVID-19. Approximately 73 students/employees have been deemed close contacts by DPH guidelines and are receiving additional correspondence from the school.

We continue to encourage all families to temperature scan and monitor students closely for any sign of potential illness. Students should remain at home if they are exhibiting any symptoms of COVID-19 including fever, new or persistent cough, headache, loss of taste or smell, fatigue and/or stomach issues (diarrhea). Please remember that the school principal should be notified if parents or students develop multiple symptoms and/or a positive COVID-19 test result.

post_text:
ATTN Floyd County Families:
This is a journey we have all taken together and the reduction in our isolation does not signify its end. We must still take measured steps and remain vigilant of the factors that nature has imposed upon us. We have created this plan and based our revisions on new knowledge and shifts in public sentiment. Outlined in the ‚ÄúReturn to Learn Plan‚Äù are a decision-making matrix and guidelines for how our schools will conduct day to day operations. Safety above all is preeminent and we have to consider that safety for some students resides within the four classroom walls, and for others we have to extend those walls to the home. During this time we ask for your grace and patience as we all navigate these quickly changing circumstances. We all long for a normal day and rest assured that day will come. In the interim please know: the situation will be monitored as closely as possible, you will be informed, and action will be taken swiftly and responsibly to protect the lives that are in our care.

post_text:
REMINDER from FCS Superintendent Dr. Wilson:
After consultation with county officials and the Georgia Department of Public Health, along with seeing the large spike in COVID-19 cases and hospitalizations, FCS has decided to cancel the July 23rd and 24th traditional graduation ceremonies to ensure the safety of FCS staff and students. We believe that having four gatherings of hundreds of people just is not safe based on our current uptick of COVID-19.

School systems around the state are considering or already have made the decision to cancel in-person graduations. Bringing together large groups from each of our school communities together with COVID-19 cases and hospitalizations on the rise, along with our plan to start with students in school in August, would just not be prudent.

Cave Spring Elementary School is at Floyd County Schools, Georgia.
June 2 at 11:48 PM ¬∑ Rome, GA ¬∑

Cave Spring Elementary has just been named a National Beta School of Merit. Cave Spring is awarded this prestigious honor for inviting membership for eligible students in grades 4th and 5th of the Junior Beta charter.

This fall, 20 students were inducted into the charter, becoming the only active elementary level Beta Club charter in Floyd County Schools.

Taking the motto, "Let us lead by serving others", students are encouraged to support their communities in service and leadership projects.

We are proud of this prestigious honor and hope for an active year for service in 2020-2021!

Tonight at 8:20 p.m. (2020 military time), Floyd County high schools will join the national ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign. Armuchee High, Coosa High, Model High, and Pepperell High will turn on the stadium lights at their respective football stadiums ONE LAST TIME. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes, honoring the Class of 2020.

Please feel free to drive by, observe, and honk your horn for the Class of 2020! Please do NOT stop or get out of your vehicle, in order to remain in compliance with the Governor‚Äôs orders for social distancing and grouping.

Even if you cannot make it by the stadium, turn on your house lights at 8:20 p.m. in recognition of the Class of 2020!

We admire the strength of this senior class, and we will get through this together! üñ§ü§çüíõüíô

post_text:
We are deeply saddened and heartbroken by the news of the death of one of our students, Vanita Richardson who was scheduled to graduate next Saturday.

We extend our deepest sympathies to the Armuchee Community and her friends and family at this time. Our thoughts and prayers are with them.

Vanita will be remembered for being a fun-loving, humble, and motivated student who was making strong plans for her future.

Even throughout the school closures, Vanita's passing is felt by all. In particular, the staff members whose lives she touched with her caring personality and big heart.

The Armuchee High social worker and counselor will be available for virtual grief and loss counseling sessions. Students who are interested should email them directly.

post_text:
Tonight at 8:20 p.m. (2020 military time), Floyd County high schools will join the national ‚ÄúBe the Light‚Äù campaign. Armuchee High, Coosa High, Model High, and Pepperell High will turn on the stadium lights at their respective football stadiums. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes, honoring the Class of 2020. This will take place every Friday evening through May 22, 2020.

Please feel free to drive by, observe, and honk your horn for the Class of 2020! Please do NOT stop or get out of your vehicle, in order to remain in compliance with the Governor‚Äôs orders for social distancing and grouping.

Even if you cannot make it by the stadium, turn on your house lights at 8:20 p.m. in recognition of the Class of 2020!

We admire the strength of this senior class, and we will get through this together!

shared_text:
Pepperell FFA and Floyd County Young Farmers
March 27 at 8:28 PM ¬∑

One of Pepperell FFA's favorite events throughout the year is the annual Spring Plant Sale held at the PHS greenhouse! Not only do Plant Sale proceeds provide travel opportunities for student members to State FFA Convention, Region Rally, Summer Leadership Camp, and local field trips, but it gives our community a time to interact with FFA members and see what is happening in PHS's Ag Ed program. Although we will miss seeing you shop in our greenhouse this year, Pepperell FFA will be providing an ONLINE sale and a scheduled drop-in order pick-up for customers April 13th-18th. Please stay tuned for details of placing your order, online payment, and pick-up scheduling. Pepperell FFA SO appreciates your support for students as we blaze new trails together!

Although we will miss seeing you shop in our greenhouse this year, Pepperell FFA will be providing an ONLINE sale and a scheduled drop-in order pick-up for customers April 13th-18th. Please stay tuned for details of placing your order, online payment, and pick-up scheduling. Pepperell FFA SO appreciates your support for students as we blaze new trails together!

March 25 at 6:17 PM ¬∑

Today Mrs. Elliott will be reading the book "Maybe Something Beautiful - How Art Transformed a Neighborhood" by F. Isabel Campoy and Theresa Howell. illustrated by Rafael Lopez.
Permission was given by the author for us to share this wonderful story.

Mrs. Elliott chose this book because of the message of joy it promotes in the community. Please help in our mission to shower our Model community with positivity by encouraging your student(s) to create and post a joyful piece of artwork using the hashtag #MESspreadsjoy. The hope is that this will help to remind our community about the importance of seeing happiness that we can all enjoy!

Georgia Department of Public Health
March 9 at 8:21 PM ¬∑

The best way to prevent #COVID19 is to practice everyday preventive behaviors like hand washing and covering your #cough or sneeze with tissue.

Hand washing is the first line of defense because washing your hands with soap and water ,for 20 seconds, kills viruses that may be on your hands.

Droplets from a cough or sneeze can spread virus. When you cough or sneeze, cover your mouth and nose with tissue, then dispose of the used tissue immediately. This protects those around you from viruses like cold, flu and COVID-19. #COVID19GA

WEATHER ALERT: Due to potential flooding that could create unsafe road conditions tomorrow morning, Floyd County Schools will be on a 2-hour delay for all staff and students. For example, if your school normally starts at 7:50 a.m., it will open at 9:50 a.m. tomorrow. Schools will dismiss at their regular time. CCA students from AHS and CHS that drive to school are to report directly to their high schools at 11:45 a.m. CCA bus riders at CHS and AHS should report directly to their school‚Äôs auditorium upon arrival.

Please be very cautious when traveling on roadways tomorrow. If you feel the commute for you or your child seems dangerous, please wait until it is safe to travel to school. If conditions worsen and a change to the school day is needed, we will notify you by 6 a.m. The safety of our staff and students is our first priority. Thank you for your patience and understanding. We look forward to seeing you tomorrow!

Students in 1st grade harvested enough lettuce from our Aquaponics and science lab to directly give back to our lunchroom! Tomorrow, we serve homegrown lettuce with our salad, available on the lunch line!

Pictured below are second graders who worked to clean the lettuce, getting it prepped and ready for the line.

We have the BEST SROs! üíô
Officer Ginger Shelly, the Model school resource officer, was chosen as Floyd County Police Department‚Äôs Officer of the Third Quarter for her calling of helping and caring for the children she works with every day. Chief Mark Wallace described her ability and passion for school work as a gift. ‚ÄúShe never misses an opportunity to speak to students and has gone out of her way to acknowledge each student she comes in contact with,‚Äù said one educator at Model. ‚ÄúShe learns their names, she checks in on them and she genuinely cares about their well-being.‚Äù
One senior recognized SRO Shelly as being one of the most influential persons in their life.

We have the BEST SROs! üíô
Officer Ginger Shelly, the Model school resource officer, was chosen as Floyd County Police Department‚Äôs Officer of the Third Quarter for her calling of helping and caring for the children she works with every day. Chief Mark Wallace described her ability and passion for school work as a gift. ‚ÄúShe never misses an opportunity to speak to students and has gone out of her way to acknowledge each student she comes in contact with,‚Äù said one educator at Model. ‚ÄúShe learns their names, she checks in on them and she genuinely cares about their well-being.‚Äù
One senior recognized SRO Shelly as being one of the most influential persons in their life.

post_text: An ultimate success for one of our students! ü•∞ü•∞ü•∞ Coosa High School
shared_text:
Carla Maddox Hammons
December 13, 2019 at 3:47 PM ¬∑

Special day for my child! He was born colored blind and recently he discovered that they offered glasses for colorblind folks! I told him to wait til after christmas and I would get him a pair.
Well....he took it all on his own(without me knowing) and set himself up a go fund page to where he could get them sooner in hopes of having some donationsü§¶‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
I tried and tried to get him to stop that campaign but he was way to adamant to get these glasses right now.
**Moral of the story.....being able to see colors each and everyday is a blessing and we fail to realize what a gift our senses really are! For someone that has never really seen what true colors are vividly-what a blessing it is to experience this for the first time!
Thank you to each one that helped my son make this moment happen!!!
Sorry but not sorry for the emotion!
Perfect Christmas present for this mamaüéÅüéÑ
**Thank you Pilestone for making this an experience he will never forget
#Pilestone

Floyd County 5th Grade Kaleidoscope Students Take on Tybee Island

Floyd County Schools 5th grade Kaleidoscope students recently traveled to the Burton 4-H Center on Tybee Island to participate in an Environmental Education Program. The Environmental Education Program is customized with specific objectives requested by visiting groups. Kaleidoscope students experienced shark dissection, marsh ecology, reptile and sea turtle education, and beach activities. Students also toured nearby Fort Pulaski and enjoyed a dolphin cruise.

Through the Environmental Education Program, students developed an awareness, knowledge, and appreciation for Georgia‚Äôs natural environment and coastal ecosystems.

View photos from their trip below.

Story contributed by Lindsey Barcomb.

Held during the third full week of October each year, National School Bus Safety Week is an active and evolving public education program and an excellent way for parents, students, teachers, motorists, school bus operators, school administrators, and other interested parties - to join forces and address the importance of school bus safety.

Today is also Bus Driver Appreciation Day. The Floyd County Board of Education would like to recognize and thank the Floyd County Schools Transportation Department for all they do to keep our children safe every single day. Bus drivers are the invaluable foundation of the FCS team.

Designed to promote school bus safety, school districts throughout the country observe School Bus Safety Week.
This year‚Äôs theme is "My School Bus, The Safest Form of Student Transportation!"

These photos are from the Transportation Department‚Äôs annual safety competition for all FCS bus drivers.
